		<credit project="CfPBoK@https://slebok.github.io/cfpbok/"/>
		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2014"></a><br><code>sle2014/paper05</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2014</a> paper:</span><br><i>Eco: A Language Composition Editor</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/LukasDiekmann.html">Lukas Diekmann</a>, <a href="../profile/LaurenceTratt.html">Laurence Tratt</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-319-11245-9_5">10.1007/978-3-319-11245-9_5</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> It presents an editor/IDE prototype supporting composed languages via incremental parsing.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> A main goal is modular language composition (combining arbitrary syntaxes).
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> It extends incremental parsing and name binding analysis to support composed syntaxes.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5h.html"><span class="tagL">T5H: Usability</span></a><ul><li> It aims to preserve the feel of a normal text editor while guaranteeing structurally valid edits.
</li></ul></li></ul>
